{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01EF66ijgYtiUUSn91pYMiJs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior for this email drafting assistant to determine the minimum test infrastructure level needed.\n\nThe system has several components:\n1. Email thread reading\n2. LLM-based draft generation\n3. Factual consistency check against knowledge base\n4. Approval workflow (blocks auto-send)\n5. A full end-to-end pipeline\n\nLet me go through each behavior:\n\n## Behavior 1: \"The generated reply references specific points from the incoming email rather than producing a generic response.\"\n\nThis is testing that the LLM takes the actual content of the email thread and uses it in the response.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: Could a pure mock miss this? If I mock the LLM to always return \"Here is my response\", a test could still pass if I just check that something was returned. BUT if I'm checking for actual references to content in the email (like \"I see you mentioned X\"), then I need the LLM to actually work on the input.\n- LLM-DEP: Does correctness depend on what the real LLM produces? YES. The behavior is about whether the LLM actually makes reference to specific points. A mocked LLM would always fail this check (or always pass). The quality of the reference depends on the real LLM's behavior.\n- Could a Unit test catch this? A unit test of the \"extract references\" logic could be tested, but the actual behavior is about the LLM generating contextual text. That requires the LLM.\n- Could an Integration test catch this? If I mock the LLM, no. I could test that the draft is passed through a reference-checking function, but the generation of contextual drafts requires a real LLM call.\n\nThis is **Agentic** because:\n- The failure mode is: \"LLM generates a generic draft that doesn't reference the email\" \n- Only a real LLM call can produce or fail to produce specific references\n- Mocking would hide the real failure\n- Different LLM calls might produce different quality of references\n\n\n- The core question is whether the LLM, when given an email thread, actually produces contextual references versus generic boilerplate. To detect this failure, I'd need to either mock the LLM with responses that are intentionally generic, or call the real LLM and verify it produces specific references. A mock could verify the system handles both good and bad outputs, but the actual generation of contextual content requires the real model.\n\n- I'm realizing the behavior is really about whether the system passes email content into the generation process at all. The failure mode would be if the email thread gets ignored entirely—the LLM receives empty or generic context and produces a draft with no connection to the actual message. I could test this at the unit level by checking whether the prompt-building function includes email-specific details, or at the integration level by wiring together email reading and draft generation with a mocked LLM to verify the prompt contains the actual email content.\n\n- But the stated behavior mentions the reply should reference \"specific points\" from the email, which suggests quality matters. That pushes toward needing a real LLM call to validate the output actually captures those details. However, I could also interpret this narrowly: the system must avoid generic responses, and I could catch that with a mock LLM that returns a fixed generic response, then verify the system rejects it or handles it differently.\n\n- The integration approach seems most practical: wire together email extraction and prompt formation, mock the LLM, and confirm the prompt includes email-specific content. This catches the core failure mode without needing the real LLM.\n\n- But if the requirement is truly about output quality—that the generated reply must contain specific references—then only an agentic test with the real LLM would validate that. Integration testing alone wouldn't catch a case where the email context is passed but the LLM still produces something generic.\n\n- I'll weight this as Integration (0.6) being the minimum to catch the main failure, with Agentic (0.35) needed for full validation and Unit (0.05) for any specificity-checking logic if it exists.\n\nFor the fact-checking behavior, the core question is whether contradictions between the draft and knowledge base are properly detected. A unit test could validate the contradiction-detection logic in isolation with mocked KB responses, but that risks missing real failures in how the KB is actually queried or how results are interpreted. Integration testing with actual KB lookups would be more robust, though the choice depends on whether the focus is on the detection algorithm itself or the end-to-end fact-checking flow.\n\nThe critical failure to catch: contradictions go undetected or are incorrectly marked as valid. This requires a concrete scenario—a draft claiming \"The policy was approved in 2020\" paired with a KB entry stating \"The policy was approved in 2021\"—and verification that the system flags the mismatch. Unit testing with controlled inputs and mocked lookups can validate the logic, though integration testing would catch issues with real KB data structures or formats that might break the detection. I'd weight this as Unit (0.7), Integration (0.25), System (0.05).\n\nFor the third behavior about disclaimers when the KB has no relevant entries, the test needs to verify the system doesn't fabricate information when knowledge is unavailable.\n\nThe core risk is LLM-dependent: the model itself must generate facts responsibly, not just that post-processing adds a disclaimer afterward. Even with a mocked LLM returning plausible-sounding statements, testing whether a disclaimer gets appended only validates the wrapper logic, not whether the real LLM actually respects instructions to avoid unsupported claims. Since correctness hinges on actual LLM behavior and instruction-following, this leans toward Agentic testing (0.6)—though a secondary integration layer could test post-processing logic if the system explicitly checks for KB support before generating content.\n\nFor the approval workflow, the key is verifying the send operation doesn't execute without explicit user consent. A unit test can mock the send function and assert it remains uncalled until approval is granted, then called afterward. This is straightforward to validate with mocks, so Unit testing dominates (0.7), with Integration testing as a fallback for the full workflow.\n\nReconsidering the blocking behavior itself—the core failure mode is a draft reaching the user without approval confirmation. Testing requires mocking both user approval and the send operation, then confirming send only triggers post-approval. This is solidly Unit/Integration territory with no external dependencies needed.\n\nFor the complete sequence spanning thread reading through approval, the end-to-end validation requires a real LLM for draft generation and a test email thread to verify all stages integrate properly. Integration testing becomes primary here since the behavior spans multiple components working together. - Test setup: Create an email mentioning a specific detail like \"Project deadline is March 31\", then either mock the LLM to capture its prompt or call it live and check if the draft references that deadline.\n- Level probabilities: Integration 0.6, Agentic 0.35, Unit 0.05, System 0.0, Workflow 0.0\n- Consistent with plan: Yes—Integration catches whether email content reaches the LLM prompt; Agentic validates the quality of references in the actual output.\n\nI'm reconsidering what minimum level actually catches real failures. The failure could stem from email content never reaching the LLM at all (Integration can detect this by mocking and inspecting the prompt), or from the LLM failing to incorporate it meaningfully (Agentic catches this with live calls). The distinction matters for test design.\n\nSince the behavior emphasizes output quality—that replies reference specific points rather than generic responses—Integration alone might miss whether the LLM actually uses the content. A mocked LLM returning \"Thank you for reaching out\" would pass an Integration test if the email was correctly passed to it, but fail the actual behavior. So Agentic testing with a real LLM is safer for validating this quality requirement. specific references in the output.\n\nAn integration test with a mocked LLM can verify that email content actually reaches the prompt—checking that the email reading module's output flows correctly into the LLM prompt construction. However, this doesn't guarantee the real LLM will generate specific references. An agentic test calling the actual LLM would be more thorough, but integration testing catches the critical failure where email data isn't being passed through at all.\n\nFor the contradiction flagging behavior, the main failure modes are: contradictions slip through undetected due to flawed logic, or false negatives where inconsistencies are incorrectly marked as consistent.\n\nA unit test works well here since the contradiction detection function can be pure—I can provide controlled draft text and knowledge base entries to verify the logic handles string matching and semantic similarity correctly. Mocking the KB lookup doesn't hide failures because I'm testing the detection logic itself, not the retrieval mechanism. Integration testing with a real knowledge base adds coverage but isn't strictly necessary for catching logic errors.\n\nFor the disclaimer behavior when KB has no relevant entries, the real failure modes involve the LLM generating unsupported facts without a disclaimer, the system failing to instruct the LLM to include one, or the draft being returned without checking KB support first. Catching the LLM behavior requires an agentic test with the actual model, but unit or integration tests with a mocked LLM can catch whether the system properly checks KB support and constructs the right instructions.\n\nThe core issue is whether the LLM actually avoids fabrication, which needs real LLM verification. If there's post-processing logic that adds a disclaimer when KB support is absent, that's testable at the integration level. The approval workflow blocking sends before user approval is straightforward to test—I need to verify that send() isn't called until explicit approval is given, which is a unit-testable control flow check.\n\nFor the end-to-end workflow, the key is testing whether all components integrate correctly: email reading, draft generation with fact-checking, and approval. Since draft generation involves the LLM, this requires agentic-level testing to validate the full sequence works with real behavior. think Workflow is the minimum: **Workflow** (0.75), Agentic (0.2), Integration (0.05), others 0.0\n\nThe pipeline's end-to-end nature—where failures could occur at reading, generation, fact-checking, or approval stages—justifies testing at the workflow level rather than isolating individual components. To catch real failures like improper email extraction, missing content in the LLM prompt, or the model ignoring provided context, I need to verify the full sequence works together, not just individual pieces in isolation. There's a distinction between testing whether the system correctly feeds email content to the LLM versus testing whether the LLM actually produces specific references in its output. A mock LLM can verify data is being passed correctly, but only a real LLM can validate the quality of the references themselves. The core question becomes: am I testing the engineering implementation or the actual behavior? Since catching a real failure means identifying when data isn't reaching the LLM in the first place, Integration-level testing with a mocked LLM addresses the root cause without relying on the LLM's non-deterministic behavior.\n\nWhen I consider whether a pure mock could miss this failure, the answer is no—if I inspect what's actually being sent to the mocked LLM, I can verify the email content is included in the prompt. The mock doesn't need to produce correct output; it just needs to expose what was passed to it. This means Integration testing (0.6) is sufficient to catch the failure, with Agentic (0.3) and Unit (0.1) playing supporting roles.\n\nBut reconsidering the actual requirement—that the draft should reference specific points from the incoming email—I realize I'm testing the system's output, not just its internal plumbing. This requires either calling the real LLM to verify it actually produces contextual responses, which introduces non-determinism and flakiness, or using an Agentic-level test that exercises the full behavior. Integration testing alone might verify the email reaches the LLM, but it won't confirm the LLM produces specific, relevant content rather than generic responses. With a real LLM, the test would verify the actual output. The key distinction is whether I'm checking that email content reaches the LLM (Integration) or whether the LLM actually produces contextual references (Agentic). Since the behavior focuses on output quality, an Agentic test with a real LLM would catch if the response lacks specific references. However, an Integration test mocking the LLM could still fail if the prompt doesn't include email details, catching the data-passing failure. Integration represents the minimum threshold needed to detect engineering mistakes, though Agentic testing better validates the full behavior.\n\nReconsidering the prompt's emphasis on catching real production failures—where users receive generic drafts instead of email-specific ones—an Agentic test becomes necessary. Unit tests with mocks would only verify that email content gets passed to the LLM, not whether the LLM actually uses it. Integration tests catch data flow problems. But only Agentic tests with the real LLM can detect if the generated output is actually generic despite correct inputs.\n\nThe behavior involves two modules coordinating (email extraction feeding into draft generation), which Integration testing could verify. However, since the behavior itself focuses on the output quality—whether it references specific points—I need Agentic-level testing to truly validate it. Unless there's a validation layer checking for specific references, which the behavior statement doesn't mention, the minimum required is Agentic.\n\nTo catch a real bug like the system producing generic drafts regardless of email content, I'd need either a real LLM with actual email input (Agentic) or a real email with a mocked LLM to verify the prompt contains the right data (Integration). The minimum is likely Integration for catching coordination failures, but Agentic for catching the actual behavior failure. Given the behavior emphasizes the output quality, Agentic is the true minimum.\n\nFor contradiction detection, a Unit test with mocked knowledge base data can verify the logic works correctly. For the disclaimer requirement, I need the real LLM to confirm it actually follows the instruction rather than fabricating facts. The approval blocking behavior can be caught with a Unit test mocking the send function. End-to-end functionality requires a Workflow test with all components integrated to catch pipeline failures.\n\nAssigning probabilities: Behavior 1 needs the actual LLM output, so Agentic testing dominates at 0.55. Behavior 2 is pure logic that Unit tests handle well at 0.75. Behavior 3 requires real LLM behavior verification at 0.55 for Agentic. Behavior 4's send blocking is straightforward Unit testing at 0.75. Behavior 5 demands full integration, making Workflow the clear choice at 0.85.\n\nI'm questioning whether Behavior 5 requires a genuine email server or if mocking the email client suffices—the description mentions \"a real email thread\" which suggests actual email infrastructure might be necessary.\n\nReconsidering the breakdown: a realistic test email should work without needing System-level components. Adjusting Behavior 5 to reflect this—Integration testing increases to account for email handling, while Workflow remains dominant since the full pipeline executes.\n\nFor Behavior 1, I need to determine if Integration or Agentic testing is more appropriate. The test uses a mock LLM with a generic response to check whether the system validates outputs properly. A mocked LLM catches some issues but won't reveal how the real model performs, suggesting Agentic testing would be more valuable for verifying actual LLM behavior.\n\nBehavior 2 works well at the Unit level since contradiction detection between draft and KB content is logic-focused and doesn't depend on KB implementation details. Behavior 3 requires Agentic testing to verify the disclaimer appears when KB support is unavailable, as this depends on real LLM behavior and how it handles missing context.\n\nBehavior 4 is a state machine test—checking that send() only triggers after approval—which Unit testing handles adequately with mocks. Behavior 5 spans the entire pipeline from email ingestion through sending, requiring all components integrated together and a real LLM for draft generation, making it a Workflow-level test.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13273,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13273},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8b132ffd-d428-40b5-951d-668bc88ed341","uuid":"b2bc86bd-7d03-4509-bac7-64b19f16f161"}
